In Java 8, the Predicate<T> interface is a functional interface in java.util.function package.
It represents a condition (boolean-valued function) of one argument and is typically used for filtering
or matching logic in Streams.

âœ… Basic Syntax
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Predicate<T> {
    boolean test(T t);

    // default methods:
    default Predicate<T> and(Predicate<? super T> other)
    default Predicate<T> or(Predicate<? super T> other)
    default Predicate<T> negate()
}

ðŸ”¸ Example 1: Filter even numbers using Predicate
import java.util.*;
import java.util.function.Predicate;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class PredicateExample1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(10, 15, 20, 25, 30);

        Predicate<Integer> isEven = num -> num % 2 == 0;

        List<Integer> evenNumbers = numbers.stream()
                                           .filter(isEven)
                                           .collect(Collectors.toList());

        System.out.println("Even numbers: " + evenNumbers); // [10, 20, 30]
    }
}

ðŸ”¸ Example 2: Combine Predicates (and, or, negate)
public class PredicateExample2 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Predicate<Integer> isEven = num -> num % 2 == 0;
        Predicate<Integer> isGreaterThan20 = num -> num > 20;

        List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35);

        // Even AND >20
        System.out.println("Even and >20:");
        numbers.stream()
               .filter(isEven.and(isGreaterThan20))
               .forEach(System.out::println); // 30

        // NOT even
        System.out.println("Odd numbers:");
        numbers.stream()
               .filter(isEven.negate())
               .forEach(System.out::println); // 15, 25, 35
    }
}

ðŸ”¸ Example 3: Predicate with Custom Object (Employee Filter)
class Employee {
    String name;
    int age;
    double salary;

    public Employee(String name, int age, double salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    public String toString() {
        return name + " - Age: " + age + " - Salary: " + salary;
    }
}

public class PredicateCustomObject {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Employee> employees = Arrays.asList(
            new Employee("John", 25, 50000),
            new Employee("Jane", 30, 60000),
            new Employee("Alex", 35, 45000)
        );

        Predicate<Employee> highSalary = emp -> emp.salary > 50000;

        employees.stream()
                 .filter(highSalary)
                 .forEach(System.out::println);

    }
}

ðŸ”¸ Use Cases of Predicate
Validations (e.g., non-empty string)
Stream filtering (filter())
Conditional checks (removeIf(), anyMatch(), allMatch())